8}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Black Reel Awards of 2018|Black Reel Awards]]\n|Best Supporting Actress\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\"imdbawards\" />\n|-\n|[[23rd Empire Awards|Empire Awards]]\n|[[Empire Award for Best Female Newcomer|Best Female Newcomer]]\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\"imdbawards\" />\n|-\n|[[44th Saturn Awards|Saturn Awards]]\n|[[Saturn Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web| date=March 15, 2018| title=Here Are The 44th Annual Saturn Awards Nominations| website=Blending Cool |url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2018/03/15/here-are-the-44th-annual-saturn-awards-nominations/| access-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[2018 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Awards]]\n|[[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie Actress \u2013 Sci-Fi/Fantasy|Choice Movie Actress: Sci-Fi]]\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/943773/teen-choice-awards-2018-avengers-infinity-war-black-panther-and-riverdale-among-top-nominees|title=Teen Choice Awards 2018: ''Avengers: Infinity War'', ''Black Panther'' and ''Riverdale'' Among Top Nominees|last=Cohen|first=Jess|work=[[E! News]]|date=June 13, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019\n| [[2019 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Action Movie Actress\n| ''Men in Black: International''\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |last1=Moreau |first1=Jordan |title='Avengers: Endgame,' 'Riverdale,' 'Aladdin' Top 2019 Teen Choice Award Nominations |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/teen-choice-awards-nominations-avengers-endgame-riverdale-1203247410/ |website=Variety |accessdate=19 July 2019 |language=en |date=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n* {{Instagram}}\n* [http://aveleyman.com/ActorCredit.aspx?ActorID=60730 Tessa Thompson](Aveleyman)\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Tessa Thompson\n|list =\n{{Black Reel Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress}}\n{{Gotham Independent Film Award for Breakthrough Actor}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thompson, Tessa}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n[[Category:American actresses of Mexican descent]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American people of Mexican descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Panamanian descent]]\n[[Category:American Shakespearean actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Bisexual actresses]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American actresses]]\n[[Category:LGBT African Americans]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT Hispanic and Latino American people]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from California]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Santa Monica College alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{distinguish|Tressa Thompson}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image       = Tessa Thompson by Gage Skidmore 3.jpg\n| caption     = Thompson at the 2019 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birth_name  = Tessa Lynne Thompson\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1983|10|3}}\n| birth_place = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| alma_mater  = [[Santa Monica College]]\n| occupation  = {{flatlist|\n*Actress\n*singer\n}}\n| yearsactive = 2002\u2013present\n| spouse      = \n| website     =\n}}\n\n'''Tessa Lynne Thompson'''<ref name=tvg /> (born October 3, 1983) is an American actress and singer. Born and raised in [[Los Angeles]], she began her acting career with the [[List of Theatre Communications Group member theatres|Los Angeles Women's Shakespeare Company]] while studying at [[Santa Monica College]]. She appeared in productions of ''[[The Tempest]]'' and ''[[Romeo and Juliet]]'', the latter of which earned her a [[NAACP Theatre Award]] nomination. Her breakthrough came with a leading roles in [[Tina Mabry]]'s independent drama film ''[[Mississippi Damned]]'' (2009) and [[Tyler Perry]]'s drama film ''[[For Colored Girls]]'' (2010). \n\nThompson gained critical acclaim for her performances in the comedy-drama ''[[Dear White People]]'' (2014), as [[civil rights]] activist [[Diane Nash]] in the historical drama ''[[Selma (film)|Selma]]'' (2014), and as [[List of Rocky characters#Bianca Taylor|Bianca Taylor]] in the sport drama films ''[[Creed (film)|Creed]]'' (2015) and ''[[Creed II]]'' (2018). She gained mainstream recognition for her starring role as [[Valkyrie (Marvel Comics)|Valkyrie]] in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] superhero films ''[[Thor: Ragnarok]]'' (2017) and ''[[Avengers: Endgame]]'' (2019).\n\nHer other films include the dark comedy ''[[Sorry to Bother You]]'' (2018), the psychological horror film ''[[Annihilation (film)|Annihilation]]'' (2018), the science fiction action film ''[[Men in Black: International]]'' (2019), and the musical romance film ''[[Lady and the Tramp (2019 film)|Lady and the Tramp]]'' (2019). On television, Thompson starred in the noir drama series ''[[Veronica Mars]]'' (2005\u20132006), the drama series ''[[Copper (TV series)|Copper]]'' (2012\u20132013), and the science fiction series ''[[Westworld (TV series)|Westworld]]'' (2016\u2013present).\n\n==Early life==\nThompson was born October 3, 1983, in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]].<ref name=tvg>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/tessa-thompson/195495 |title=Tessa Thompson |website=[[TV Guide|TVGuide.com]] |archivedate=September 8, 2016 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160908193547/http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/tessa-thompson/195495 |url-status = dead}}</ref><!--cited source, TV Guide, also verifies middle name Lynne--> She was raised between Los Angeles and [[Brooklyn]], New York.<ref name=embrace>Thompson in {{cite news|first=Kai |last=Morgan |date=May 5, 2014 |url=http://embraceyoumagazine.com/2014/05/05/exclusive-tessa-thompson-on-varied-dreams-and-effecting-change/ |title=Exclusive: Tessa Thompson on varied dreams and effecting change |publisher=EmbraceYouMagazine.com |accessdate=July 21, 2015 |archivedate=March 31, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160331215533/http://embraceyoumagazine.com/2014/05/05/exclusive-tessa-thompson-on-varied-dreams-and-effecting-change/ |url-status = live}}</ref> Her father, singer-songwriter Marc Anthony Thompson, of the musical collective [[Chocolate Genius, Inc.]],<ref name=embrace /> is of [[Afro-Panamanian]] descent,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.essence.com/awards-events/red-carpet/black-women-hollywood/tessa-thompson-speech-mexican-mother-pride-blackness/|title=Tessa Thompson Shares How Her Mexican Mother Helped Her Take Pride In Her Blackness: 'She Wanted Me To Be Brave'|website=Essence}}</ref> while her mother is of Caucasian and Mexican ancestry.<ref name=\"zakarin\">{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/movies/tessa-thompson-selma-dear-white-people-106538108532.html |title=Tessa Thompson on Selma, Dear White People, and Her Breakthrough Year |first=Jordan |last=Zakarin |publisher=[[Yahoo! Movies]] |date=December 29, 2014 |accessdate=April 10, 2017 |quote=...a Panamanian father and half Mexican, half white mother. |archivedate=September 21, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921194122/https://www.yahoo.com/movies/tessa-thompson-selma-dear-white-people-106538108532.html |url-status = live}}</ref> She attended [[Santa Monica High School]] where she played [[Hermia]] in a student production of ''A Midsummer Night's Dream''. She then attended [[Santa Monica College]] (SMC), where she studied [[cultural anthropology]]. While at SMC, she also attended lectures by Lisa Wolpe of [[List of Theatre Communications Group member theatres#J \u2013 L|Los Angeles Women's Shakespeare Company]] (LAWSC).<ref name=\"behrens\">{{cite news|last=Behrens |first=Deborah |date=July 11, 2012 |url=http://thisstage.la/2012/07/tessa-thompson-returns-to-shakespeare-as-rosalind/ |title=Tessa Thompson Returns to Shakespeare as Rosalind |publisher=@ This Stage (LA Stage Alliance) |accessdate=July 21, 2015 |archivedate=March 4, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304052515/http://thisstage.la/2012/07/tessa-thompson-returns-to-shakespeare-as-rosalind/ |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Tessa Thompson - DSC 0109 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Thompson in 2014]]\n\n===Theatre===\nIn 2002, Thompson made her professional stage debut in as one of three actors portraying the role of [[Ariel (The Tempest)|Ariel]] in LAWSC's production of ''[[The Tempest]]''. In 2003, she appeared as [[Juliet Capulet|Juliet]] in ''Romeo and Juliet: Antebellum New Orleans, 1836'' with The Theatre @ Boston Court in [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]], California, which earned her an [[NAACP Theatre Awards|NAACP Theatre Award]] nomination.<ref name=\"behrens\" />\n\nIn 2016, Thompson appeared in the [[off-Broadway]] run of the [[Lydia R. Diamond]] play ''Smart People'' at [[Second Stage Theatre]], starring alongside [[Mahershala Ali]], [[Joshua Jackson]] and Anne Son.<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/smart-people-theater-review-863215|title='Smart People': Theater Review|magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Valence Media]]|location=Los Angeles, California|language=en|date=February 11, 2016|access-date=March 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2016/legit/reviews/smart-people-review-joshua-jackson-1201702655/|title=Off Broadway Review: 'Smart People' with Joshua Jackson|last=Stasio|first=Marilyn|last2=Stasio|first2=Marilyn|date=February 12, 2016|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|language=en|access-date=March 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Television===\nThompson made her first television appearance in a 2005 episode of the [[CBS]] series ''[[Cold Case]]'' in the role of a [[lesbian]] [[Rum-running|bootlegger]] from the 1930s. In the same year, she rose to fame as she landed the role of [[Jackie Cook]] on the [[UPN]]/[[The CW Television Network|CW]] [[neo-noir]] drama series ''[[Veronica Mars]]'', starring as a series regular in season two.<ref name=\"zakarin\" /><ref name=\"behrens\" /> In 2006, she appeared on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] medical drama ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Lindsay|last=Peoples|url=https://www.thecut.com/2016/02/meet-tessa-thompson.html|title=Tessa Thompson on Race, Hollywood, and Her Impending Stardom|website=The Cut|publisher=[[New York Media]]|location=New York City|language=en|date=February 12, 2016 |access-date=March 27, 2019}}</ref> In 2007, she was a part of the cast on the CW's short-lived drama ''[[Hidden Palms]]'', portraying Nikki Barnes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/30/arts/television/30bell.html|title=Pretty Faces With Plenty of Troubles, and Secrets|last=Bellafante|first=Ginia|date=May 30, 2007|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[New York Times Company]]|location=New York City|access-date=March 27, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2007/tv/reviews/hidden-palms-1200559015/|title=Hidden Palms|last=Lowry|first=Brian|date=May 25, 2007|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|language=en|access-date=March 27, 2019}}</ref> She worked on guest star roles on ''[[Life (NBC TV series)|Life]]'' and ''[[Private Practice (TV series)|Private Practice]]'', and appeared in [[Heroes (season 4)|season four]] of ''[[Heroes (U.S. TV series)|Heroes]]''.\n\nIn 2010, she had a guest role as the wife of a detective on ''[[Detroit 187]]''. In 2012, Thompson had a guest role as Gavin Doran's daughter, Sasha, on ''[[666 Park Avenue]]''. In 2013, she starred in [[BBC America]]'s first original series ''[[Copper (TV series)|Copper]]''.<ref name=\"behrens\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/worldwide/020412copper|title=BBC \u2013 BBC America's first original drama, Copper, to premiere August 19 \u2013 Media Centre|website=www.bbc.co.uk |language=en-GB|access-date=July 17, 2018}}</ref> In 2016, she began a starring role in the [[HBO]] [[science-fiction]] drama series ''[[Westworld (TV series)|Westworld]]'' as board director Charlotte Hale.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/09/westworld-tessa-thompson-cast-hbo-1201533978/|title=HBO Drama 'Westworld' Adds Tessa Thompson As Series Regular|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=September 18, 2015|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|language=en|access-date=March 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/11/westworld-who-is-charlotte-hale-host-arnolds-daughter-charlotte-is-charlie-williams-daughter|title=Is Westworld Hiding One Last Maddening Twist?|last=Robinson|first=Joanna|date=November 30, 2016|magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]]|location=New York City|language=en|access-date=March 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Film===\n[[File:Sylvester Stallone, Tessa Thompson, and Michael B. Jordan promoting Creed at the Philadelphia Art Museum.JPG|thumb|right|Thompson with [[Sylvester Stallone]] and [[Michael B. Jordan]] promoting ''Creed'' in 2015]]\nThompson's first feature film appearance was in the 2006 remake of the horror film ''[[When a Stranger Calls (2006 film)|When a Stranger Calls]]'' playing the role of Scarlett. Thompson was next seen opposite [[Mary Elizabeth Winstead]] in the dancing film ''[[Make it Happen (film)|Make it Happen]]'' in 2008.\n\nIn 2010, Thompson appeared in [[Tyler Perry]]'s stage play adaptation ''[[For Colored Girls]]'', after she directly approached Perry to be cast in the film.<ref name=\"behrens\"/> In 2014, she starred as Samantha White in [[Justin Simien]]'s [[Sundance Film Festival|Sundance]]-winning comedy ''[[Dear White People]]''. That same year, Thompson played civil rights activist [[Diane Nash]] in [[Ava DuVernay]]'s [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] biopic ''[[Selma (film)|Selma]]''.<ref name=\"griggspall\">{{cite news|last=Grigg-Spall |first=Holly |date=n.d. |url=http://issuemagazine.com/tessa-thompson/ |title=Tessa Thompson |publisher=IssueMagazine.com |accessdate=July 21, 2015 |archivedate=March 29, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329054644/http://issuemagazine.com/tessa-thompson/ |url-status = live}}</ref> In 2015, she appeared in [[Ryan Coogler]]'s ''[[Rocky (film series)|Rocky]]'' sequel ''[[Creed (film)|Creed]]'',<ref name=\"zakarin\" /> and in [[Nate Ruess]]' short film ''[[The Grand Romantic]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ruess|first1=Nate |title=The Grand Romantic Chapter 1 debut |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/post/idsa.19378bfc-4502-11e5-b9a5-d5765b744c3b|website=Apple Music Connect}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, Thompson was cast as [[Valkyrie (Marvel Comics)|Valkyrie]]<ref name=\"Cast\">{{cite web|url=http://marvel.com/news/movies/26203/marvel_studios_confirms_stellar_new_cast_members_of_the_highly_anticipated_thor_ragnarok|title=Marvel Studios Confirms Stellar New Cast Members of the Highly Anticipated 'Thor: Ragnarok'|publisher=[[Marvel Comics|Marvel.com]]|date=May 20, 2016| first= Marc |last=Strom|accessdate=May 20, 2016| archivedate= April 10, 2017| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170410160821/https://news.marvel.com/movies/26203/marvel_studios_confirms_stellar_new_cast_members_of_the_highly_anticipated_thor_ragnarok/ |url-status = live}}</ref> in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] superhero film ''[[Thor: Ragnarok]]'', which was released on November 3, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/04/tessa-thompson-joins-the-marvel-universe-thor-ragnarok-1201735551/|title=Tessa Thompson Joins The Marvel Universe In 'Thor: Ragnarok'|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|last=Busch|first=Anita|date=April 11, 2016|accessdate= April 10, 2017 |archivedate=February 23, 2017 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170223113836/http://deadline.com/2016/04/tessa-thompson-joins-the-marvel-universe-thor-ragnarok-1201735551/ |url-status = live}}</ref> She then appeared in the science-fiction horror film ''[[Annihilation (film)|Annihilation]]'', which was released on February 23, 2018. In June 2017, Thompson was cast in the science-fiction comedy ''[[Sorry to Bother You]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/06/tessa-thompson-lakeith-stanfield-steven-yeun-movie-sorry-to-bother-you-1202113786/|title=Tessa Thompson, Lakeith Stanfield, Steven Yeun To Star In 'Sorry To Bother You'|last=Busch|first=Anita |website=Deadline Hollywood|date= June 15, 2017|access-date=May 19, 2018}}</ref> which was released on July 6, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/watch-lakeith-stanfield-in-wild-sorry-to-bother-you-trailer-w520411|title=Watch Lakeith Stanfield Make Millions With 'White Voice' in Wild 'Sorry to Bother You' Trailer|last=Blistein|first=Jon|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date= May 17, 2018|access-date=May 19, 2018}}</ref> She reprised her role as [[List of Rocky characters#Bianca Taylor|Bianca Taylor]] in ''[[Creed II]]'', which was released on November 21, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/creed-2-director-steven-caple-jr-1202626542/|title=Steven Caple Jr. to Direct 'Creed 2' Starring Michael B. Jordan and Sylvester Stallone (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=December 11, 2017|work=Variety |accessdate=April 18, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThompson reprised her role as Valkryie in the superhero sequel film ''[[Avengers: Endgame]]'', which was released on April 26, 2019. She starred as Agent M in the ''[[Men in Black (film series)|Men in Black]]'' spin-off film, ''[[Men in Black: International]]'', opposite [[Chris Hemsworth]], her co-star from ''Thor: Ragnarok'' and ''Avengers: Endgame''. The film was released on June 14, 2019.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys |title=Tessa Thompson to Join Chris Hemsworth in 'Men in Black' Spinoff (Exclusive) |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/tessa-thompson-join-chris-hemsworth-men-black-spinoff-1095965|accessdate=April 18, 2018|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 21, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://collider.com/men-in-black-reboot-title/|title=The 'Men in Black' Reboot Is Titled 'Men in Black International'|last=Chitwood|first=Adam|date=December 5, 2018|website=Collider|language=en-US|access-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt 2019 [[San Diego Comic-Con]], it was announced that Thompson would reprise her role as Valkyrie in the superhero film ''[[Thor: Ragnarok#Sequel|Thor: Love and Thunder]]''. Valkyrie, after being declared King of New Asgard, will begin searching for her queen, revealing herself to be the MCU's first major [[LGBT]] character.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/thor-star-tessa-thompson-will-play-marvels-first-lgbtq-superhero-1225891 |title='Thor' Star Tessa Thompson Teases Valkyrie as Marvel's First LGBTQ Superhero |date=July 20, 2019 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |first=Mia |last=Galuppo |access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nThompson is also a singer-songwriter. She has in the past been a member of the Los Angeles-based indie electro soul band [[Caught A Ghost|Caught a Ghost]],<ref>{{Cite magazine|first=Adrienne|last=Gaffney|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6312224/dear-white-people-star-tessa-thompson-on-her-music-career|title='Dear White People' Star Tessa Thompson Spills About Her Secret Music Career|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Valence Media]]|location=Los Angeles, California|access-date=November 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media|last=Lifeminute|title=Caught a Ghost Talk Tour and Upcoming Album Human Nature|date=December 3, 2013|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TLiqb5_D_Rc|access-date=November 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|first=Emily|last=Zemler|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/music/news/a24169/caught-a-ghost-exclusive-premiere/|title=Tessa Thompson and Jesse Nolan Make Music Magic in Caught A Ghost|date=January 20, 2014|work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]|publisher=[[Hearst Magazines]]|location=New York City|access-date=November 25, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> and contributed to the soundtracks for both ''[[Creed (film)|Creed]]'' and ''[[Creed II]]'', for which she co-wrote and performed several songs with producer [[Moses Sumney]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/watch-creed-2-star-tessa-thompson-explain-what-inspired-the-songs-she-wrote-for-her-character-video-13178031|title=Watch Tessa Thompson Explain Her Inspiration For The Songs She Wrote For 'Creed 2'|last=Brayson|first=Johnny|work=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]|publisher=Bustle Digital Group|location=New York City|date=November 21, 2018|access-date=November 25, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/11/creed-ii-cast-tessa-thompson-rihanna.html|title=How Rihanna Inspired Tessa Thompson's Creed II Character|last=Lee|first=Chris|work=[[Vulture.com|Vulture]]|publisher=[[New York Media]]|location=New York City|date=November 20, 2018|access-date=November 25, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nThompson has a younger half-sister, Zsela Thompson, who is a singer-songwriter.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/26/style/zsela-thompson-music.html|title= Zsela  Sings Moody Ballads for the Fashion and Art Set |first= Dalya |last=Benor|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[New York Times Company]]|location=New York City|date=April 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThompson said in a 2018 interview that she is \"attracted to men and also to women\",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.net-a-porter.com/us/en/porter/article-502e16f70e0351fa |date=June 29, 2018 |title=Break the Mold, with Tessa Thompson |first=Jane |last=Mulkerrins |accessdate=January 2, 2019 |website=[[YOOX Net-a-Porter Group|Net-A-Porter]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/06/tessa-thompson-bisexual-comes-out-janelle-monae-1201979637/|title=Tessa Thompson Comes Out, Says She and Janelle Monae Wrestle With Privacy vs. Visibility|last=Sharf|first=Zack|website=[[IndieWire]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=June 29, 2018 }}</ref> but states she chooses not to label herself [[bisexuality|bisexual]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Pollard|first=Alexandra|title=Tessa Thompson interview: 'Men should have the responsibility to deal with their toxicity'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/tessa-thompson-interview-creed-ii-2-sexuality-men-bisexual-acting-michael-b-jordan-metoo-a8658881.html|work=[[The Independent]]|publisher=Independent Print Ltd.|location=London, England|date=November 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n<!-- Add references to reliable sources (preferably secondary) to verify films/role(s) (see WP:FILM/R)\n\nPlease note: do NOT use \"rowspans\" per WP:FILMOGRAPHY -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n! class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[When a Stranger Calls (2006 film)|When a Stranger Calls]]''\n|Scarlet\n|\n| style=\"text-align: center;\"  | <!-- Add refs to reliable source(s) here -->\n|-\n| 2008\n|''[[Make It Happen (film)|Make It Happen]]''\n|Dana\n|\n| style=\"text-align: center;\"  | <!-- Add refs to reliable source(s) here -->\n|-\n| 2008\n|''{{sortname|The|Human Contract}}''\n|Waitress\n|\n| style=\"text-align: center;\"  | <!-- Add refs to reliable source(s) here -->\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Mississippi Damned]]''\n|Kari Peterson\n|\n| style=\"text-align: center;\"  | <!-- Add refs to reliable source(s) here -->\n|-\n| 2010\n|''[[Everyday Black Man]]''\n|Claire\n|\n| style=\"text-align: center;\"  | <!-- Add refs to reliable source(s) here -->\n|-\